					</div>
				</div>
			
	
			<a class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-btn" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapseSummary1479" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseSummary1479" data-lexicon-show="show" data-lexicon-hide="hide">
				abstract
			</a>
			<div class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse collapse" id="collapseSummary1479">
				<div class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-inner">
					<p>The text examines visibility of  work of female artists in Polish art field. It’s based on my own interviews with professionally active female artists. I try to reconstruct cultural conditions of their work and values set down by art discourse, which is strictly correlated with capitalistic reality. In my analysis I point to work as an operation connected with preparing piece of art, creative process, organizing display etc., but also to practices usually not considered as work – for example – “cultivation of contactness”. Gender has important role to play in these analyses of visibility and transparency of artistic work.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		
</li><li class="c-issue-toc__article c-issue-toc__article--has-translation" data-aricle-no="01">
	<h4 class="c-issue-toc__article-title" id="1481"><a href="/en/archive/2018/21-invisible-labor/mierle-laderman-ukeles-maintenance-andas-art-work">Mierle Laderman Ukeles’ Maintenance and/as (Art) Work</a></h4>
	<h5 class="c-issue-toc__article-authors"><!--Author:--><a href="/en/bio?id=1480">Andreas Petrossiants</a></h5>
	
				<a class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-btn" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapseDoi1481" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseSummary1481" data-lexicon-show="show" data-lexicon-hide="hide">
					citation
				</a>
