				<div class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-inner">
					<p><span>The article is an attempt to reflect on the issue of content moderation on the Internet, in particular, visual content. The author refers to the book </span><em><span>Algor</span></em><em><span>ithms of Oppression</span></em><span>, in which Safiya Umoja Noble describes oppressive discrimination systems functioning within the network, as well as two narratives describing the work of the so-called content moderators – artistic installation <em>Dark Content </em>and documentary <em>The Cleaners</em>. The author asks about the ways of the existence of a digital image that has been removed from the web, raises the issue of its non-presence, and also reflects on the place of power and supervision in the ontology of digital visuality.</span></p>
